<subSubSection id="BADD651FFFC7FFF729F68D94FEA2F799" pageId="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="F2783694FFC7FFF729F68D94FE62F9C9" blockId="25.[136,1452,158,2057]" pageId="25">
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF729F68D94FED2FA84" bold="true" box="[189,328,1274,1300]" pageId="25">Comments:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName id="35C74D17FFC7FFF7282F8D94FD2CFA84" authorityName="Zambrano, Hagsater &amp; Solano. A. Habit. B. Flower" authorityYear="2021" box="[356,694,1274,1300]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Epidendrum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="viridi-ochraceum">
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF7282F8D94FD2CFA84" box="[356,694,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="25">Epidendrum viridi-ochraceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the Spathiger group, and is distinguished by the narrowly oblong, non-bilobed, mucronate leaves, ochre-orange flowers with green column, a sweet nocturnal odor, petals linearoblanceolate, 3-veined and the lip obovate-pandurate, acute, with an entire callus and three fleshy, parallel, low ribs. The most similar species is the Mesoamerican 
<taxonomicName id="35C74D17FFC7FFF72BD68C09FCC7FA10" authorityName="Schlechter" authorityYear="1911" box="[669,861,1382,1408]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Epidendrum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cardiophorum">
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72BD68C09FCC7FA10" box="[669,861,1382,1408]" italics="true" pageId="25">E. cardiophorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which can be distinguished by the larger plants (
<quantity id="353F9B71FFC7FFF72CC58C08FF30FA35" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="25" unit="cm" value="35.0">35 cm</quantity>
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF729FA8CE5FF55FA34" box="[177,207,1419,1444]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
<quantity id="353F9B71FFC7FFF7299D8CE4FE80FA35" box="[214,282,1418,1445]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="25" unit="cm" value="15.0">15 cm</quantity>
tall), bilobed leaves (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72B468CE5FDB1FA34" box="[525,555,1419,1444]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
entire), green flowers (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72A7A8CE5FCD5FA34" box="[817,847,1419,1444]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
ochre-orange), ovate-elliptic dorsal sepal (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72C648CE5FAD4FA34" box="[1327,1358,1419,1444]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
oblonglanceolate), 5-veined petals (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF7289B8CC1FE74FA58" box="[464,494,1455,1480]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
3-veined), and an ovate-cordiform lip (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72AF88CC1FC48FA58" box="[947,978,1455,1480]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
obovate-pandurate) (
<bibRefCitation id="96564B65FFC7FFF72D888CC0FF5FFA7C" author="Jimenez, R. &amp; Hagsater, E." pageId="25" pagination="1310" refId="ref15574" refString="Jimenez, R. &amp; Hagsater, E. (2010) Epidendrum cardiophorum Schltr. In: Hagsater, E. &amp; Sanchez-Saldana, L. (Eds.) The genus Epidendrum, Part 9. Icones Orchidacearum 13: pl. 1310. [Instituto Chinoin, Mexico]" type="journal article" year="2010">Jiménez &amp; Hágsater 2010</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="35C74D17FFC7FFF729978CBCFC76FA7C" authority="(Williams 1946: 371 - 372) Hagsater" authorityName="Hagsater" baseAuthorityName="Williams" baseAuthorityPageNumber="371 - 372" baseAuthorityYear="1946" box="[220,1004,1490,1516]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Epidendrum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="angustisegmentum">
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF729978CBCFDDBFA7C" box="[220,577,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="25">Epidendrum angustisegmentum</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="96564B65FFC7FFF72B1F8CBCFCEFFA7C" author="Williams, L. O." box="[596,885,1490,1516]" pageId="25" pagination="1 - 404" refId="ref16133" refString="Williams, L. O. (1946) Flora of Panama: Orchidaceae. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 33: 1 - 404. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 2394519" type="journal article" year="1946">Williams 1946: 371–372</bibRefCitation>
) Hágsater
</taxonomicName>
(1999: pl. 308), from 
<collectingCountry id="8AD07604FFC7FFF72DB18CBCFAE2FA7C" box="[1274,1400,1490,1516]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="25">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="8AD07604FFC7FFF729C38C99FF7EF981" box="[136,228,1527,1553]" name="Panama" pageId="25">Panama</collectingCountry>
, is also similar, but it can be distinguished by the elliptic leaves (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72A888C99FC7BF980" box="[963,993,1527,1552]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
narrowly oblong), the yellow to yellowgreen flowers (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF7287F8F75FEC8F9A4" box="[308,338,1563,1588]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
ochre-orange), ovate dorsal sepal (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72BA98F75FC9BF9A4" box="[738,769,1563,1588]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
oblong-lanceolate), and an ovate, bicallose lip (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72C688F75FADBF9A4" box="[1315,1345,1563,1588]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
obovatepandurate, with an entire callus).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F2783694FFC7FFF729F68F0CFEA2F799" blockId="25.[136,1452,158,2057]" pageId="25">
The Colombian 
<taxonomicName id="35C74D17FFC7FFF7283B8F0CFCECF9EC" authority="Hagsater &amp; Uribe (2019" authorityName="Hagsater &amp; Uribe" authorityYear="2019" box="[368,886,1634,1660]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Epidendrum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="beatricis">
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF7283B8F0CFDF8F9EC" box="[368,610,1634,1660]" italics="true" pageId="25">Epidendrum beatricis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="96564B65FFC7FFF72B238F0CFCECF9EC" author="Hagsater, E. &amp; Uribe, V." box="[616,886,1634,1660]" pageId="25" pagination="1707" refId="ref15303" refString="Hagsater, E. &amp; Uribe, V. (2019) Epidendrum beatricis Hagsater &amp; Uribe. In: Hagsater, E. &amp; Santiago, E. (Eds.) The genus Epidendrum, Part 13. Icones Orchidacearum 17 (1): pl. 1707. [Instituto Chinoin, Mexico]" type="journal article" year="2019">Hágsater &amp; Uribe (2019</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
: pl. 1707), differs in the leaves apically bilobed (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72CC68F0DFA31F9EC" box="[1421,1451,1635,1660]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
entire), flowers without fragrance (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72B5A8FE9FDAAF930" box="[529,560,1671,1696]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
producing a sweet nocturnal odor), 5-veined dorsal sepal (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72D8F8FE9FB78F930" box="[1220,1250,1671,1696]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
8-veined), linearoblong petals (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF728678FC5FED0F954" box="[300,330,1707,1732]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
linear-oblanceolate), and a sub-rectangular-ovoid, bicallose lip (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72D5F8FC5FBA8F954" box="[1044,1074,1707,1732]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
obovate-pandurate, with an entire callus). 
<taxonomicName id="35C74D17FFC7FFF729AF8FA0FD2FF978" authority="Jacquin (1760: 29)" authorityName="Jacquin" authorityPageNumber="29" authorityYear="1760" box="[228,693,1742,1768]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Epidendrum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rigidum">
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF729AF8FA0FE4BF978" box="[228,465,1742,1768]" italics="true" pageId="25">Epidendrum rigidum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="96564B65FFC7FFF728908FA0FD2FF978" author="Jacquin, N." box="[475,693,1742,1768]" pageId="25" pagination="29 - 30" refId="ref15530" refString="Jacquin, N. (1760) Species Gynandria-Diandria. Enumeratio Systematica Plantarum. Apud Theodorum Haak, Lugduni Batavorum. pp. 29 - 30." type="book chapter" year="1760">Jacquin (1760: 29)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from the Antilles and Northern South America, differs in having green flowers (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF728648F9DFED7F89C" box="[303,333,1779,1804]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
ochre-orange), a narrowly obovate dorsal sepal (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72A218F9DFC12F89C" box="[874,904,1779,1804]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
oblong-lanceolate), narrowly oblanceolate petals (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF729DA8E79FF2AF8A0" box="[145,176,1815,1840]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
linear-oblanceolate), and an ovate, bicallose lip (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72BA48E79FC97F8A0" box="[751,781,1815,1840]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
obovate-pandurate, with transverse entire callus). Finally, 
<taxonomicName id="35C74D17FFC7FFF729C38E54FEE0F8C4" authorityName="Zambrano, Hagsater &amp; Solano. A. Habit. B. Flower" authorityYear="2021" box="[136,378,1850,1876]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Epidendrum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="viridium">
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF729C38E54FEE0F8C4" box="[136,378,1850,1876]" italics="true" pageId="25">Epidendrum viridium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also described herein, differs in the narrowly oblong-elliptic, emarginate leaves (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72C6B8E55FAA4F8C4" box="[1312,1342,1851,1876]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
narrowly oblong, obtuse-mucronate), flowers green turning yellow-green when old, producing a camphorated-lemon odor (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72CC68E31FA31F8E8" box="[1421,1451,1887,1912]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
ochre-orange, with a sweet odor), oblong-ovate, obtuse dorsal sepal (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF72AD98EEDFC2AF80C" box="[914,944,1923,1948]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
oblong-elliptic, acute), oblong, obtuse petals (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF729DA8EC9FF2AF850" box="[145,176,1959,1984]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
linear-oblanceolate, slightly acute), and an oblong-obovate, rounded lip with short parallel ribs not running the entire length of the lip (
<emphasis id="C0B3EA86FFC7FFF728DF8EA5FE29F874" box="[404,435,1995,2020]" italics="true" pageId="25">vs.</emphasis>
obovate-pandurate, acute, with three fleshy, low ribs, the mid-rib running down the entire lip to the apex).
</paragraph>
